w\" fetchpriority=\"high\"></picture><div class=\"image-link-expand\"><div class=\"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset\"><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container restack-image\"><svg role=\"img\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 20 20\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke=\"var(--color-fg-primary)\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><g><title></title><path d=\"M2.53001 7.81595C3.49179 4.73911 6.43281 2.5 9.91173 2.5C13.1684 2.5 15.9537 4.46214 17.0852 7.23684L17.6179 8.67647M17.6179 8.67647L18.5002 4.26471M17.6179 8.67647L13.6473 6.91176M17.4995 12.1841C16.5378 15.2609 13.5967 17.5 10.1178 17.5C6.86118 17.5 4.07589 15.5379 2.94432 12.7632L2.41165 11.3235M2.41165 11.3235L1.5293 15.7353M2.41165 11.3235L6.38224 13.0882\"></path></g></svg></button><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container view-image\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-maximize2 lucide-maximize-2\"><polyline points=\"15 3 21 3 21 9\"></polyline><polyline points=\"9 21 3 21 3 15\"></polyline><line x1=\"21\" x2=\"14\" y1=\"3\" y2=\"10\"></line><line x1=\"3\" x2=\"10\" y1=\"21\" y2=\"14\"></line></svg></button></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p>We often roll our eyes at first responders when they joke in the face of tragedy.</p><p>It can feel inappropriate — like they’re laughing at pain.</p><p>But if you’ve ever stood beside one in the aftermath of horror, you realize something deeper: they’re not mocking it. They’re surviving it.</p><p>That’s gallows humor — the strange, defiant laughter born at the edge of death.</p><p>And oddly enough… Jesus had it too.</p><h3><strong>1. The Irish Inheritance</strong></h3><p>I’m Irish.</p><p>And like most Irish things, that means I come from a people who learned to laugh through tears.</p><p>Sarcasm and irony weren’t hobbies for our ancestors — they were armor. Forged through centuries of oppression, famine, and humiliation, humor became a sacred survival skill. It was how we kept our humanity when the world denied it.</p><p>When the Irish came to America, we brought that instinct with us — especially into the work no one else wanted. The police, the firefighters, the nurses, the undertakers. The jobs that stared death in the face.</p><p>So when people hear a dark joke in a …</p>"}